<Layout title="Bordeaux Wine Region" description="A guide to Bordeaux — the world's most famous wine region, home to legendary châteaux and the art of the blend.">
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6 py-20">
    <p class="text-amber-600 font-medium tracking-wider uppercase text-sm mb-3">Wine Regions</p>
    <h1 class="font-display text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold text-stone-900 mb-6">Bordeaux: The Art of the Blend</h1>
    <p class="text-stone-500 text-sm mb-8">By Roberto Carli, CMS · 12 min read</p>

    <div class="prose prose-stone max-w-none">
      <p class="text-lg text-stone-600 leading-relaxed">Bordeaux is the most recognizable wine region in the world. Its name is synonymous with serious, age-worthy red wine, its classification system dates to 1855, and its top estates — Lafite Rothschild, Margaux, Haut-Brion, Mouton Rothschild, Latour — are among the most famous luxury brands on Earth. But Bordeaux is far more diverse and accessible than its reputation suggests.</p>

      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-10">Left Bank vs. Right Bank</h2>
      <p>The Gironde estuary and the Garonne and Dordogne rivers divide Bordeaux into two philosophically distinct halves:</p>

      <h3 class="font-display text-xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-6">Left Bank (Médoc, Graves, Pessac-Léognan)</h3>
      <p>Gravel soils, larger estates, and <strong>Cabernet Sauvignon-dominant</strong> blends define the Left Bank. The wines are structured, tannic when young, and built to age. Key appellations: Pauillac (home to three of the five First Growths), Saint-Julien (polished elegance), Margaux (perfumed finesse), and Saint-Estèphe (firm, earthy). Pessac-Léognan, closer to the city of Bordeaux, produces outstanding reds and the region's finest dry whites (Sauvignon Blanc/Sémillon blends).</p>

      <h3 class="font-display text-xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-6">Right Bank (Saint-Émilion, Pomerol, Fronsac)</h3>
      <p>Clay and limestone soils favor <strong>Merlot-dominant</strong> blends, producing wines that are generally rounder, softer, and more approachable in youth. Saint-Émilion has its own classification system (reclassified every decade), topped by estates like Cheval Blanc and Ausone. Pomerol — tiny, unclassified, and home to the legendary Pétrus — produces some of the most sought-after and expensive wines in the world.</p>

      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-10">The 1855 Classification</h2>
      <p>When Napoleon III ordered a ranking of Bordeaux's top wines for the 1855 Paris Exposition, he created a hierarchy that still dominates the market 170 years later. The Left Bank wines were ranked from First Growth (Premier Cru) to Fifth Growth (Cinquième Cru) based on their trading prices at the time.</p>
      <p>The classification has barely changed since — only Mouton Rothschild was elevated (from Second to First Growth, in 1973). Critics argue the system is outdated, and many Fifth Growths now outperform Second Growths. But the prestige of the First Growths remains immense, and the classification continues to influence pricing worldwide.</p>

      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-10">The Grapes</h2>
      <p>Bordeaux is a blending region. Virtually all red Bordeaux is a blend of some combination of:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Cabernet Sauvignon</strong> — structure, tannin, blackcurrant, cedar. Dominates on the Left Bank.</li>
        <li><strong>Merlot</strong> — roundness, plum, chocolate, softness. Dominates on the Right Bank.</li>
        <li><strong>Cabernet Franc</strong> — aromatics, violets, graphite. A supporting player in most blends but the star at estates like Cheval Blanc.</li>
        <li><strong>Petit Verdot</strong> — color, spice, intensity. Used in small quantities for added depth.</li>
        <li><strong>Malbec</strong> — increasingly rare in Bordeaux (it found its true home in Argentina) but historically part of the blend.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>White Bordeaux blends Sauvignon Blanc with Sémillon (and sometimes Muscadelle). Dry whites from Pessac-Léognan are world-class. Sweet whites from Sauternes and Barsac — made from botrytis-affected grapes — are among the greatest dessert wines ever produced.</p>

      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-10">Bordeaux on a Budget</h2>
      <p>The First Growths and cult Right Bank estates may cost $500–$5,000+ per bottle, but the vast majority of Bordeaux is affordable and excellent:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Cru Bourgeois</strong> — a separate classification for quality estates below the 1855 ranked growths. Many are stunning at $20–$40.</li>
        <li><strong>Satellite appellations:</strong> Lalande-de-Pomerol, Montagne-Saint-Émilion, Côtes de Bourg, Côtes de Blaye — genuine Bordeaux character at $12–$25.</li>
        <li><strong>Second wines:</strong> Many classified estates produce a second label at a fraction of the price. Carruades de Lafite, Le Petit Mouton, and Echo de Lynch-Bages are accessible entry points to legendary estates.</li>
        <li><strong>White Bordeaux:</strong> Dry Sauvignon Blanc/Sémillon blends from Entre-Deux-Mers and basic Graves — $10–$18 and terrific value.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-10">Vintages Matter in Bordeaux</h2>
      <p>Bordeaux's maritime climate creates significant vintage variation. Great years (2010, 2015, 2016, 2018, 2019, 2020) produce rich, concentrated wines with long aging potential. Challenging years (2013, 2017) can still produce enjoyable wines from the best estates, often at a discount. For drinking now, the 2015 and 2016 vintages offer an exceptional combination of quality and relative availability.</p>
